                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d601">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115/1046: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-12-17T21:00:00+09:00"
                            >December 17, 1940—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 18—10:24 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1329. Department’s 530, December 10, 5 p.m. Interference with reexportation of
                    American owned goods from Shanghai to Hong Kong. In an interview with the
                    Foreign Minister today I made oral representations supported by a signed note
                    protesting against the unwarranted interference by Japanese authorities in
                    Shanghai with these shipments and requesting that such interference be
                    immediately discontinued.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department, repeated to Chungking and Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
